variables = ['cylinders', 'displacement', 'horsepower', 'weight', 'acceleration', 'model_year', 'origin']

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

for i, var in enumerate(variables, 1):
    plt.subplot(2, 4, i)
    sns.scatterplot(x=var, y='mpg', data=df)
    plt.title(f'Relationship between {var} and mpg')
    plt.xlabel(var)
    plt.ylabel('mpg')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('relationships_with_mpg.png')
plt.show()

# Step 4: Perform linear regression using OLS
X = df['horsepower']
y = df['mpg']

model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
predictions = model.predict(X)

# Print out the statistics
print(model.summary())

# Step 5: Plot the results including the regression line

# Handle the 'name' column
df_ = df.drop('name', axis=1)

# Prepare the target variable
y = df_['mpg']

# Apply different transformations
transformations = {
    'log': np.log,
    'sqrt': np.sqrt,
    'reciprocal': lambda x: 1 / x,
    'square': np.square
}

# Function to perform OLS regression and return summary
def perform_ols(X, y):
    X = sm.add_constant(X)
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    return model

# Store results for each transformation
results = {}

# Original model without transformation
X = df_.drop('mpg', axis=1)
original_model = perform_ols(X, y)
results['original'] = original_model


# Apply transformations and perform regression
for name, func in transformations.items():
    X_transformed = df_.drop('mpg', axis=1).apply(func)
    model = perform_ols(X_transformed, y)
    results[name] = model


# Compare results
for name, model in results.items():
    print(f"\nModel with {name if name != 'original' else 'no'} transformation")
    print(model.summary())

# Handle the 'name' column
df_ = df.drop('name', axis=1)

# DROP FEATURES
# df_ = df_.drop('cylinders', axis=1)
# df_ = df_.drop('horsepower', axis=1)
# df_ = df_.drop('acceleration', axis=1)
# df_ = df_.drop('displacement', axis=1)


transformations = {
    'log': np.log,
    'sqrt': np.sqrt,
    'reciprocal': lambda x: 1 / x,
    'square': np.square
}

for transformation in transformations:
    # Step 3: Prepare the data for regression
    X = df_.drop('mpg', axis=1)
    y = df_['mpg'].apply(transformations[transformation])
    X = sm.add_constant(X)  # Adds a constant term to the predictor

    # Step 4: Perform the regression using OLS
    model = sm.OLS(y, X).fit()
    predictions = model.predict(X)

    # Print out the statistics
    print(model.summary())

    # Step 5: Evaluate the model and feature importance
    # - Check the p-values of the features
    # - Use statistical tests and methods like AIC, BIC for model selection

    # Optionally, visualize some residual plots
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.residplot(x=predictions, y=model.resid, lowess=True)
    plt.xlabel('Fitted values')
    plt.ylabel('Residuals')
    plt.title('Residuals vs Fitted')
    plt.show()
